all centre workers by Sapu. The South African Police Service (SAPS) has brought an application at the Labour Court to stop what it claims is intimidation of call centre workers by Sapu. The South African Police Service (SAPS) has brought an application at the Labour Court to stop what it claims is intimidation of call centre workers by Sapu.        Sapu stated that it is considering legal action against SAPS for what it claims are threats of disciplinary charges if the strike continues. Sapu stated that it is considering legal action against SAPS for what it claims are threats of disciplinary charges if the strike continues. Sapu stated that it is considering legal action against SAPS for what it claims are threats of disciplinary charges if the strike continues.        The memorandum of demands was received and signed by Calvin Humbles from the office of the President. He said that the document would be forwarded to the correct people and that a response would be issued in seven working days. DM The memorandum of demands was received and signed by Calvin Humbles from the office of the President. He said that the document would be forwarded to the correct people and that a response would be issued in seven working days. DM The memorandum of demands was received and signed by Calvin Humbles from the office of the President. He said that the document would be forwarded to the correct people and that a response would be issued in seven working days.  The memorandum of demands was received and signed by Calvin Humbles from the office of the President. He said that the document would be forwarded to the correct people and that a response would be issued in seven working days.  The memorandum of demands was received and signed by Calvin Humbles from the office of the President. He said that the document would be forwarded to the correct people and that a response would be issued in seven working days.  DM DM DM        Photo: Striking 10111 call centre workers marched to t